{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "The late Charles W. Mills advances a powerful critique of political liberalism, asserting the centrality of racial subordination in modernity.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Mills proposes an alternative approach to normative political theorizing: a 'black radical Kantianism' (BRK).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "He maintains that Kant had pioneered modern scientific racism that rationalized slavery and colonial expansion.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "And yet, the project of BRK aims to reshape Kant's republicanism in the light of 'the realities of racial domination.'",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "In this essay, I show how a black radical Kantianism should rethink the requirements of justice in the light of the circumstances of injustice.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "With Du Bois as my guide, my account of BRK focuses on the black American historical experience of the failure of Reconstruction to incorporate black freedmen (e.g., ex-slaves) into the polity as free, equal, and independent civic fellows.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "BRK puts pressure on an inherent weakness in Kant's system of public right.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "That weakness manifests in Kant's neglect to sketch the historical development of public standards of political judgment or to anchor their development to excluded groups making public use of reason in the circumstances of injustice.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "My BRK intervention updates Kant's original account of public right by drawing on Du Bois's Marxist critique of exploitation in the wake of American Reconstruction and the U.S. Civil War.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Given Du Bois's defense of black freedmen's political demands, I propose public standards of judgment that target the unequal effective capacity of wage laborers to command political liberty and productive power.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Mills argues that Kant's republicanism in (1) intention and (2) conception does not redress racial subordination.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Kant's original system excludes blacks, people of color, and women as civic equals.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "In his intention, then, he flouts these groups' claims to equal freedom.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The second claim -that the very conceptual foundation of his republicanism is exclusionary -is far more controversial.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Mills supports the second claim about the inherent conceptual limitation of Kant's 'ideal' theory.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "He calls for its substantive revision in the light of the circumstances of injustice.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "BRK canvasses available resources in the history of modern philosophy for political critique.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "It enlists historical figures besides Kant in its service, if their insights are useful for dismantling white supremacist power structures.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "BRK builds on a Kantian notion of freedom as the principled self-determination of a people who impose constraints on their institutions because those constraints are necessary to secure everyone's equal freedom.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "The project of BRK embraces a 'black radical' reading of any historical figure whose insights can promote a people's political and economic self-determination in the circumstances of injustice.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "BRK assumes that a political philosophy should be an action-guiding practical philosophy that has purchase for modern times.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "Kant's mature political theory of The Metaphysics of Morals (1797) and Perpetual Peace (1795) is not well suited to guide public reasoning in the light of racial (or gender) realities.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "His theory lacks a critical social theoretical account of how social identity can undermine -or protect, as the case may be -a person's effective power of choice in a system of public right with respect to their access to rights and resources.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "BRK foregrounds the black historical experience to make the case that political exclusion and exploitation are relevant obstacles to freedom and thereby challenges the white public's ideological entrenchment.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "Du Bois provides two insights for the development of a universalizable standard of judgment, putting BRK's method to use to dismantle white supremacist power structures.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "Contra Kant, Du Bois asserts that freedmen's vocal resistance should have (1) secured their equal public standing to contribute to an actual, popular will and (2) redressed the dependence of propertyless laborers on white-controlled assets and capital.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU27": {
      "text": "Freedmen's insights into the effects of Reconstruction legislation were -and still are -germane for guiding public thinking about the redistribution of rights and resources to advance justice for all by overturning unjustifiable structures of asymmetric dependence in politics and labor.",
      "label": "premise"
    }
  },
